# Adding a label for Sex. Human readable from number to string
sex_color <- factor(dataset$sex,levels = c(0, 1), labels=c("Male","Female"))
# Get the age group of people's age
age_group <- cut(dataset$age, seq(0, 100, 10))

Two Plots displaying the distribution of a single continuous variable.

# Plot for continuous variable.
# Plot show the are group on x-axis and total count on y-axis.
# Distinguished by color for Male and Female
ggplot(data = dataset, mapping = aes(x = age, fill=sex_color)) + 
  geom_bar() + 
  ggtitle("Histogram plot showing age group") + 
  xlab("Age Group") + 
  ylab("Total count of age group")

# Plots for continuos variable
ggplot(data=dataset, mapping = aes(chol, colour = sex_color)) + 
  geom_histogram(fill = "white",
                 bins = 15)  + 
  ggtitle("Histogram showing Cholestrol levels") + 
  xlab("Cholestrol levels") + 
  ylab("Level Count") +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

Two plots displaying information about a single categorical variable

# This plot shows age group of people with ST depression induced by exercise
ggplot(data=dataset, mapping = aes(x = age, y = oldpeak, colour = sex_color)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  scale_x_discrete(labels = c("0" = "Male", "1" = "Female")) + 
  ggtitle("Plot showing ST depression level of people") + 
  xlab("Age") + 
  xlim(c(0, 100)) + 
  ylab("ST Depression Level") + 
  theme(legend.position = "top")
## Scale for 'x' is already present. Adding another scale for 'x', which will

# This plot shows Cholestrol and ST depression level of people distinguished by Sex
ggplot(data=dataset, mapping = aes(x = chol, y = oldpeak, colour = sex_color)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  ggtitle("Relationship between two variables") + 
  xlab("Cholestrol levels") + 
  ylab("ST depression induced by exercise") + 
  theme(legend.position = "top")

# This plot shows Cholestrol and ST depression level of people distinguished by Age Group
ggplot(data=dataset, mapping = aes(x = thalach, y = oldpeak, colour = age_group)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  ggtitle("Relationship between two variables") + 
  xlab("Maximum Heart Rate Achieved") + 
  ylab("ST depression induced by exercise") + 
  theme(legend.position = "top")

Answers to Project Questions:

Answer-1: Data visualization is important in understanding data set in the following ways: 1) The visual context such as graphs and maps, etc gives us a clear idea of information in a precise way. 2) It provides an interactive, quick and comprehend way for the human mind to understand the data easily. 3) The available data sets and the insights provide aid in decision analysis to decision makers. 4) Moreover, Unbiased data sets without inaccuracies allows access to the right kind of information and data visualization to represent that information and keep it relevant.

Answer-2: Data visualization is important to communicating important aspects of data set in the following ways: 1) To communicate the information clearly and efficiently via the plots and graphs 2) It becomes easy to identify the patterns within large data sets 3) It helps the users to analyze the data and give proper evidences 4) Visualization helps to understand the data sets better to measure its impact on the business and communicates the insight visually to internal and external audiences. 5) Moreover, this makes the data more natural for the human mind to comprehend and therefore makes it easier to identify trends, patterns, and outliers within large data sets

Answer-3: The Role which integrity plays as an analyst when creating a data visualization for communicating results to others are: 1) To make even the large and/or complex data more understandable, accessible and usable 2) To transform, improve and integrate the data depending on the business requirements provided 3) To combine the dataset results across multiple sources 4) To deliver the data in a useful and appealing way to the audience or users 5 To define and mention all the data variables clearly 6) To ensure the consistency of the data and avoid distorting the information and facts provided in the dataset

Answer-4: More variables in data visualization increases misinterpretation of information in datasets which result in least clarity.So we need to limit visualization to as few variable as possible.Any Data visualization with exceeding 4 variables will be clutter and confusion are failure of design not attributes of information result in least effective visualization .When we exceed this number for maximum variable at the same time in a two axis chart have too much statistics and intersection between correlated variable .This moderately increases the incoherence between data.
